===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|husbonde|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|hūsbonda}}, {{term/t|ang|hūsbunda||male head of a household, householder, master of a house}}, probably from {{etyl|non|en}} {{term|húsbóndi||lang=non|master of house}}, from {{term|hús||house|lang=non}} + {{term|bóndi||dweller, householder|lang=non}}, equivalent to {{compound|house|bond|t2=serf, slave|lang=en}}.

Rather not ''bond'' = serf, but present participle of WestScand. ''búa'', EastScand. ''bôa'' = to build, to plow; cf. German ''bauen, der Bauende''. Cognate with Icelandic {{term|húsbóndi||head of household|lang=is}}, Faroese {{term|húsbóndi||husband|lang=fo}}, Norwegian {{term|husbond||head of household, husband|lang=no}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|husbonde||master|lang=sv}}, {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|husbonde||husband|lang=da}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} The [[master]] of a [[house]]; the [[head]] of a [[family]]; a [[householder]].
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A [[tiller]] of the [[ground]]; a [[husbandman]].
#* '''1596''', {{w|Edmund Spenser}}, ''The Faerie Queene'', IV.3:
#*: a withered tree, through '''husbands''' toyle, / Is often seene full freshly to have florisht {{...}}
#* Hakewill
#*: the painful '''husband''', ploughing up his ground
#* Evelyn
#*: He is the neatest '''husband''' for curious ordering his domestick and field accommodations.
# {{context|archaic|lang=en}} A [[prudent]] or [[frugal]] [[manager]].
#* Fuller
#*: God knows how little time is left me, and may I be a good '''husband''', to improve the short remnant left me.
# A [[man]] in a marriage or marital relationship, especially in relation to his spouse.
#* Blackstone
#*: The '''husband''' and wife are one person in law.
#: ''You should start dating so you can find a suitable '''husband'''.''
# The [[male]] of a pair of [[animal]]s.
#: {{rfquotek|Dryden}}
# {{context|UK|lang=en}} A [[manager]] of [[property]]; one who has the care of another's belongings, [[owndom]], or [[interests]]; a [[steward]]; an [[economist]].
# A large [[cushion]] with arms meant to support a person in the sitting position.
#: ''While reading her book, Sally leaned back against her '''husband''', wishing it were the human kind.''
# {{context|UK|_|dialectal|lang=en}} A [[poll]]ed [[tree]]; a [[pollard]].

